Visit this link to learn more on how

In [ ]:
# Creating a distance column depending on the longitude and latitude
def haversine(df):
    """
    Calculate the distance in kilometers between two points on  earth
    
    Parameters:
      Dataframe with (lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2) as columns in that order
    """

    # convert decimal degrees to radians
    lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2 = map(np.radians, [df.iloc[:,0], df.iloc[:,1], df.iloc[:,2], df.iloc[:,3]])
    
    # haversine formula
    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1
    a = np.sin(dlat/2)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2)**2
    c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
    
    # Radius of earth in kilometers. Use 3956 for miles. Determines return value units.
    r = 6371
    return c * r
  
bikes['distance']=haversine(bikes[['start_station_longitude','start_station_latitude','end_station_longitude','end_station_latitude']])

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 bike trips in the dataset with 16 features and 1 made by us(distance)

Data columns Purpose Valid values
duration_sec Time taken in the trip as seconds Int64
start_time
end_time		 Time stamp when the user Started & Ended the trip Datetime
start_Station_id
end_Station_id		 Unique value of the Starting & Ending station -
start_Station_name
end_Station_name		 The name of the station name corresponding to the id -
start_station_latitude
end_station_latitude		 The latitude of the Starting & Ending Station Float64 [-90,90]
start_station_longitude
end_station_longitude		 The longitude of the Starting & Ending Station Float64 [-180,180]
distance The straight line distance between the two stations in kilometers
It's obviously not an accurate representative of the distance covered but we might need it		 Float64 km
bike_id Unique Value for the bike id -
user_type The state of the user ['Subscriber', 'Customer']
member_birth_year
member_gender		 The birth year and gender of our user -
['Male', 'Female','Other']
bike_share_for_all_trip Wither the bike was shared or not ['Yes', 'No']

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the duration of the trips in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that user_type and distance will have the strongest effect on each trips's duration: if he is a customer , the less the duration and the less distance less the duration. I also think that the other features of trips: member_gender, member_birth_year,distance, and bike share, will have effects on the duration, though to a much smaller degree than the main effect of user_type.

We noticed From the histogram and the BoxPlot that the duration_sec column has a lot of outliers so let us filter them
using the knowledge of that the data which are not outliers lies in the range (Q1 - 1.5 IQR, Q3 + 1.5 IQR)

  • Q1: First Quartile represents the 25th mark of the data.
  • Q3: Third Quartile represents the 75th mark of the data.
  • IQR : Inter Quartile Range which is (Q3 - Q1)
In [ ]:
def remove_outliers(df: pd.DataFrame, col: str) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """
    Getting the DataFrame and the column name then filter the data from outliers based on this column
    """
    #Getting the Q1 and Q3 using the quantile method providing the percentage we want
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(.25)
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    #Quering the dataframe based on the conditions we said then returning the dataframe
    return df.query(f"{col}>{Q1-1.5*IQR} and {col}<{Q3+1.5*IQR}")

bikes2=remove_outliers(bikes,'duration_sec')
